# About This Exercise
**Title:** Load Data into Hive database clouddev
**Objective:** 
        Copy data from local host to hdfs
        Load data into Hive database clouddev staging tables
        Use Insert Table As Select to load data into Hive database clouddev managed tables
**File locations:** 
        hostname:/var/data/clouddev
        hdfs:/warehouse/tablespace/data/clouddev
**Successful outcome:** Managed hive database
**Before you begin:** N/A
**Related lessons:** Ranger

paragraphs.text:
%md

### CDP Recommended Practice for Managed Databases

####This exercise represents a CDP recommended practice for batch loading a Hive managed database where the 
####data is encrypted with a KMS key and formatted as ORC data blocks. The data is encrypted as it is loaded into hdfs and 
####remains encrypted as it is moved into an external staging table and then into a managed table. 
####Rerun this processes to continuously load batch data into a Hive managed database.

msg.data:
CDP Recommended Practice for Managed Databases

This exercise represents a CDP recommended practice for batch loading a Hive managed database where the

data is encrypted with a KMS key and formatted as ORC data blocks. The data is encrypted as it is loaded into hdfs and

remains encrypted as it is moved into an external staging table and then into a managed table.

Rerun this processes to continuously load batch data into a Hive managed database.

## Copy Data into HDFS

paragraphs.title: 2 - List the cloudsale dataset
paragraphs.text:
%sh

ls /var/data/clouddev

paragraphs.title: 3 - Make tmp directory for clouddev
paragraphs.text:
%sh

rm -r /tmp/clouddev
mkdir /tmp/clouddev

msg.data: rm: cannot remove ‘/tmp/clouddev’: No such file or directory

paragraphs.title: 4 - Use tar to extract the gz files into /tmp/clouddev
paragraphs.text:
%sh

tar -xvzf /var/data/clouddev/consent_data.tar.gz -C /tmp/clouddev/
tar -xvzf /var/data/clouddev/eu_country.tar.gz -C /tmp/clouddev/
tar -xvzf /var/data/clouddev/us_customer.tar.gz -C /tmp/clouddev/
tar -xvzf /var/data/clouddev/ww_customer.tar.gz -C /tmp/clouddev/

paragraphs.title: 5 - Delete existing data in hdfs data
paragraphs.text:
%sh

echo ${PASSWD} | su - dana_dev -c "hdfs dfs -rm -skipTrash /warehouse/tablespace/data/clouddev/*"

msg.data: Password: rm: `/warehouse/tablespace/data/clouddev/*': No such file or directory

%md

### If no data exists this will result in an error. Continue.

paragraphs.title: 6 - Load datafiles into hdfs
paragraphs.text:
%sh

#echo ${PASSWD} | su -l ${CDPADMIN} -c "hdfs dfs -mkdir -p /warehouse/tablespace/data/clouddev"
#echo ${PASSWD} | su -l ${CDPADMIN} -c "hdfs dfs -chown -R hive:hive /warehouse/tablespace/data"


echo ${PASSWD} | su -l dana_dev -c "hdfs dfs -put /tmp/clouddev/* /warehouse/tablespace/data/clouddev/"
echo ${PASSWD} | su -l dana_dev -c "hdfs dfs -ls /warehouse/tablespace/data/clouddev"

paragraphs.title: 19 - Important Note on Truncate Staging Tables
paragraphs.text:
%md

####By default in CDP, TRUNCATE TABLE is supported only on managed tables. Do not attempt to run TRUNCATE TABLE on the staging tables, as they are external tables. It will produce an error. Hive does not manage the physical data for external tables. The recommended practices is to drop the staging table and to then delete the HDFS data. This practice is demonstrated in these exercises.

Hive does not manage the physical data for external tables. The recommended practices is to drop the staging table and to then delete the HDFS data. This practice is demonstrated in these exercises.
